const Q_CRK_2016=[{"id": "objective>CRK>2016>1", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Who did Saul collect letters from that permitted him to persecute the Lord's disciples?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The chief priest </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Augustus Caesar</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">King Herod  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The high priest</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically in the book of Acts 9:1-2, it is recorded that Saul (later known as Paul) obtained letters from the high priest to the synagogues in Damascus, authorizing him to arrest any followers of 'the Way' (early Christians) he found there and bring them back to Jerusalem. Therefore, Saul collected letters from the high priest that permitted him to persecive the Lord's disciples.</div>", "topic": "OPPOSITION TO THE GOSPEL MESSAGE : PERSECUTION BY SAUL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>2", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">For giving out free will to the saints, Paul commended the Church in </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ephesus  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Rome</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Macedonia</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Thessalonica</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the New Testament of the Bible, specifically in 2 Corinthians 8:1-5, Apostle Paul commends the churches in Macedonia for their generosity. Despite their affliction and deep poverty, they gave liberally and beyond their means to the saints (fellow believers). Therefore, Paul commended the Church in Macedonia for giving out free will to the saints.</div>", "topic": "CHRISTIAN GIVING : THE IMPORTANCE OF CHRISTIAN GIVING"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>3", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">What action of Abraham produced the seal of God on His promises to him? </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Covenant   </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Consecration</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Sacrifice</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Obedience</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The action of Abraham that produced the seal of God on His promises to him was his obedience. In Genesis 22:18, it is stated that 'In your seed all the nations of the earth shall be blessed, because you have obeyed My voice.' This shows that it was Abraham's obedience to God that sealed the promises God made to him.</div>", "topic": "THE COVENANT : GOD'S COVENANT WITH ABRAHAM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>4", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The book of the Law was found by  </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Hilkiah the priest</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Shaphan the son of Azaliah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">King Josiah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Adaiah of Bozcath</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The book of the Law was found by Hilkiah the priest during the reign of King Josiah. This is recorded in 2 Kings 22:8 where it is stated that 'Hilkiah the high priest said to Shaphan the secretary, 'I have found the Book of the Law in the house of the LORD.' This shows that it was Hilkiah the priest who found the book of the Law.</div>", "topic": "RELIGIOUS REFORMS IN JUDAH : CLEANSING OF THE TEMPLE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>5", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">At Delilah's third interrogation of Samson to discover the source of his strength, he replied his strength can only leave him if </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they bound him with new ropes   </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they weaved the seven locks of his head </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">his hair was shaved</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he was bound with seven undried fresh bowstrings</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">(Judges 13-15) Samson lies to Delilah about the source of his strength for the third time. <br/>  <br/> Delilah said to Samson, \"Until now you have mocked me and told me lies. Tell me what you may be bound with.\" And he said to her, \"If you weave the seven locks of my head into the web of the loom\"; so she wove it tightly with the batten of the loom, and said to him, \"The Philistines are upon you, Samson!\" But he awoke from his sleep, and pulled out the batten and the web from the loom. Then she said to him, \"How can you say, 'I love you,' when your heart is not with me? You have mocked me these three times, and have not told me where your great strength lies.\" <br/> </div>", "topic": "A MAN AFTER GOD'S OWN HEART: THE EARLY LIFE OF DAVID"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>6", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"\"..O Nebuchadnezzar, we have no need to answer you in this matter..\"\"  <br/>  What was the reaction of Nebuchadnezzar to the statement above by Shedrach, Meshach and Abednego?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">They had faith in God to deliver them   </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">They were cast into the burning fiery furnace </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">They were sent on exile </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">They were cast into the lion's den</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the biblical story of Shedrach, Meshach, and Abednego, the three men refused to bow down to a golden image set up by King Nebuchadnezzar. When they made the statement, Nebuchadnezzar was furious and ordered that they be thrown into a burning fiery furnace. This is found in Daniel 3:16-20.</div>", "topic": "FAITH, COURAGE AND PROTECTION : EXAMPLES OF DANIEL, SHADRACH, MESHACH AND ABEDNEGO"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>7", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"This illness is not unto death, it is for the glory of God...\"  <br/>  In which of the miracles of resuscitation did Jesus make the statement above? </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The raising of Jairus' daughter   </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The raising of the widow's son </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The raising of Lazarus</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The raising of peter mother-in-law</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement \"This illness is not unto death, it is for the glory of God...\" was made by Jesus in the context of the miracle of the resurrection of Lazarus. This can be found in the Bible, John 11:4. Therefore, the correct answer is 'The raising of Lazarus'.</div>", "topic": "MIRACLES : MIRACLES OF RESUSCITATION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>8", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The sign of God's covenant with Noah was the  </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">blood    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">rainbow </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">raven </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">rain</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The sign of God's covenant with Noah was the rainbow. After the flood, God made a covenant with Noah and all living creatures that He would never again destroy the earth with a flood. As a sign of this everlasting covenant, God set a rainbow in the clouds. This can be found in the Bible, Genesis 9:13. Therefore, the correct answer is 'rainbow'.</div>", "topic": "THE COVENANT : THE FLOOD AND GOD'S COVENANT WITH NOAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>9", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Acts, for one to be a witness in the body of Christ, he must  </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">receive power    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be a good follower </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be baptised </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">speak in tongues</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Acts 1:8, Jesus told his disciples that they would receive power when the Holy Spirit comes upon them and they would be his witnesses in Jerusalem, and in all Judea and Samaria, and to the ends of the earth. Therefore, to be a witness in the body of Christ, one must receive power from the Holy Spirit.</div>", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION OF THE CHURCH : THE MISSION OF THE CHURCH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>10", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the unwise decisions of Solomon was that he  </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">began to worship other gods in Egypt    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ceded part of Israel to Tyre </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">entered into marriage with foreign women </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">refused to honour David his father</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 1 Kings 11:1-4, it is recorded that King Solomon loved many foreign women in addition to Pharaoh's daughter. These women turned his heart after other gods, and his heart was not fully devoted to the Lord his God, as the heart of David his father had been. This was an unwise decision because it led him to idolatry, which is against God's commandments.</div>", "topic": "DECISION-MAKING : UNWISE POLICIES OF SOLOMON AND REHOBOAM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>11", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">What was the cause of Nehemiah's sorrow while in exile? </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He was tired of staying in a foreign land     </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Sanballat and Tobiah planned to kill him </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He received bad news about Jerusalem </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He didn't get support from the King</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Nehemiah, it is recorded that Nehemiah was sorrowful because he received news about the broken walls of Jerusalem and the distress of the people there. This is found in Nehemiah 1:3-4, where it says, 'They said to me, 'Those who survived the exile and are back in the province are in great trouble and disgrace. The wall of Jerusalem is broken down, and its gates have been burned with fire.' When I heard these things, I sat down and wept.' Therefore, the correct answer is 'He received bad news about Jerusalem'.</div>", "topic": "CONCERN FOR JUDAH : RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF JUDAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>12", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Peter in his teaching on humility enjoins believers to always humble themselves under the  </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">leadership of the Church   </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mighty hand of God </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Law </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">authority</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 1 Peter 5:6, Peter instructs believers to 'Humble yourselves, therefore, under God's mighty hand, that he may lift you up in due time.' This verse clearly indicates that believers are to humble themselves under the mighty hand of God, not under the leadership of the Church, the Law, or any authority. Therefore, the correct answer is 'mighty hand of God'.</div>", "topic": "HUMILITY : MEANING AND REQUIREMENTS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>13", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Jesus,Son of David, have mercy on me !\"  <br/>  Who made the statement above?  </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The paralytic at the pool    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The blind man </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Zacchaeus </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Centurion's servant</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement \"Jesus, Son of David, have mercy on me!\" was made by the blind man, Bartimaeus, in the Bible (Mark 10:47). He was a beggar who heard that Jesus was passing by and cried out for mercy. His faith made him receive his sight.</div>", "topic": "JESUS' TEACHINGS ABOUT HIMSELF : THE RESURRECTION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>14", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The man sent from God to bear witness to the light was  </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jesus    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Prophet Isaiah </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">John the Baptist </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Peter</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The man sent from God to bear witness to the light was John the Baptist. This is stated in the Bible in the book of John 1:6-8. John the Baptist was sent to bear witness of the Light (Jesus Christ) so that all through him might believe. He was not the Light, but was sent to bear witness of that Light.</div>", "topic": "JESUS' TEACHING ABOUT HIMSELF: THE DOOR THE LAMB AND THE GOOD SHEPHERD"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>15", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Hosea, God would punish the house of Jehu for the blood of   </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Naboth    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jezreel </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Uriah </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jabesh Gilead</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Hosea, God promised to punish the house of Jehu for the bloodshed at Jezreel. This is because Jehu had killed all the descendants of Ahab in Jezreel as a fulfillment of Elijah's prophecy. However, Jehu did not follow the law of God with all his heart, but became like the house of Jeroboam who led Israel to sin. Therefore, God promised to avenge the blood of Jezreel upon the house of Jehu.</div>", "topic": "PUNISHMENT AND HOPE : THE SITUATIONS THAT LED TO THE PUNISHMENT OF ISRAEL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>16", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"This is the prophet Jesus from Nazareth of Galilee.\" The statement above during the Triumphant Entry was made by the  </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">disciples     </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">chief priest </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">crowd </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">children</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement \"This is the prophet Jesus from Nazareth of Galilee.\" was made by the crowd during the Triumphant Entry of Jesus into Jerusalem. The crowd recognized Jesus as a prophet and acknowledged His place of origin, Nazareth of Galilee. This is recorded in the Gospel of Matthew 21:11.</div>", "topic": "THE TRIUMPHAL ENTRY AND THE CLEANSING OF THE TEMPLE : TRIUMPHAL ENTRY AND THE CLEANSING OF THE TEMPLE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>17", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Blessed are you, Simon Bar-Jonah...\"When did Jesus make the statement above?  </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">After Peter denied Him    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">During the feeding of the five thousand </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When Peter revealed who He is  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When He walked on the sea</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jesus made the statement \"Blessed are you, Simon Bar-Jonah...\" when Peter revealed who He is. This event is recorded in Matthew 16:13-20. In this passage, Jesus asked His disciples who people say He is. After hearing their responses, He asked them who they think He is. Peter responded by saying that Jesus is the Christ, the Son of the living God. Jesus then blessed Peter, calling him Simon Bar-Jonah, and told him that this revelation was not from flesh and blood, but from His Father in heaven.</div>", "topic": "THE GREAT CONFESSION : THE SIGNIFICANCE OF THE GREAT CONFESSION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>18", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Is it you, you troubler of Israel?\".  <br/>  Why did Ahab refer to Elijah as the troubler of Israel in the statement above </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Elijah had killed four hundred and fifty prophets of Baal</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Elijah stopped the worship of Baal in Israel </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Elijah had caused drought and famine for three years </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Elijah pronounced evil against Ahab's wife, Jezebel</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ahab referred to Elijah as the troubler of Israel because Elijah had caused drought and famine for three years. This is recorded in 1 Kings 17:1, where Elijah, by the word of the Lord, declared to Ahab that there would be neither dew nor rain in the next few years except at his word. This caused a severe famine in Samaria (1 Kings 18:2). Ahab blamed Elijah for this trouble (1 Kings 18:17), hence referring to him as the troubler of Israel.</div>", "topic": "THE SUPREMACY OF GOD : RELIGIOUS TENSION AND THE POWER OF GOD ON MOUNT CARMEL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>19", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">All the calamity that befell Jerusalem after the death of King Josiah were as a result of  </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">their worship of other gods     </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the atrocities of their women </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the sins of Manasseh </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the high places that were defiled</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The calamities that befell Jerusalem after the death of King Josiah were as a result of the sins of Manasseh. Manasseh was a king of Judah who, according to the Hebrew Bible, committed such abominable acts as idolatry and witchcraft, and he led Judah into such severe sin that it provoked God to destroy the kingdom. His sins were said to have provoked God to anger, leading to the calamities that befell Jerusalem.</div>", "topic": "PUNISHMENT AND HOPE : THE SITUATIONS THAT LED TO THE PUNISHMENT OF ISRAEL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>20", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God compared Israel to a harlot because she  </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">was unrepentant    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">was worthless like the harlot </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">followed after other gods </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">continuosly disobeyed him</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God compared Israel to a harlot because she followed after other gods. In the Bible, harlotry is often used metaphorically to describe idolatry or unfaithfulness to God. Israel, despite being chosen and loved by God, often turned to worship other gods, which is likened to a woman being unfaithful to her husband. Therefore, the comparison of Israel to a harlot is due to her idolatry.</div>", "topic": "SOCIAL JUSTICE, TRUE RELIGION AND DIVINE LOVE:SOCIAL JUSTICE AND TRUE RELIGION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>21", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">What happened after Samuel anointed David as King? </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">His eyes were opened to see the task ahead  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The spirit of God came mightily upon him </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The atmosphere was filled with smoke </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He was filled with extraordinary powers</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">After Samuel anointed David as King, the spirit of God came mightily upon him. This is recorded in the Bible in 1 Samuel 16:13, where it says 'So Samuel took the horn of oil and anointed him in the presence of his brothers, and from that day on the Spirit of the LORD came powerfully upon David.' Therefore, the correct answer is option 2.</div>", "topic": "A MAN AFER GOD'S OWN HEART: DAVID'S SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>22", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Foxes have holes and birds of the air have nests, but the Son of man has nowhere to lay his head.\"  <br/>  The statement above by Jesus implies that  </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">we should prepare against the rainy day    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">believers should be as cunning as foxes </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">as believers we should have a house of our own </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">we should surrender all for the kingdom's sake</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement 'Foxes have holes and birds of the air have nests, but the Son of man has nowhere to lay his head.' by Jesus implies that we should surrender all for the kingdom's sake. This statement is found in Matthew 8:20 and Luke 9:58, and it is often interpreted as Jesus emphasizing the cost of discipleship. Jesus was saying that following Him might mean giving up physical comforts and security. Therefore, the correct answer is option 4.</div>", "topic": "DISCIPLESHIP : THE DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>23", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">During the time of Moses, the congregation of Israel planned to choose a captain and return to Egypt because  </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">of the report brought by spies     </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they were tired of eating the same kind of food </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the host of Pharaoh was approaching their camp </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">of Moses delayed at Mount Sinai</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Numbers 13:31-32, the spies that Moses sent to scout the land of Canaan returned with a discouraging report about the land. They reported that the people who dwell in the land were strong, and the cities were fortified and very large. This report made the congregation of Israel to lose faith and they planned to choose a captain and return to Egypt.</div>", "topic": "OBEDIENCE AND DISOBEDIENCE :EXAMPLES OF ADAM, COLLECTION OF MANNA, THE GOLDEN CALF, MOSES AND SAUL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>24", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">What was the reward of the Hebrew midwives when they refused to obey the instruction given to them by Pharaoh?  </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God speared their lives    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God blessed them abundantly </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God gave them families </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God exempted them from plaque</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Exodus 1:15-21, the Hebrew midwives, Shiphrah and Puah, feared God and did not do as the king of Egypt commanded them, but saved the male children alive. Therefore, God dealt well with the midwives and the people multiplied and grew very mighty. And because the midwives feared God, He gave them families.</div>", "topic": "OBEDIENCE AND DISOBEDIENCE : EXAMPLES OF ABRAHAM, HEBREW MIDWIVES AND DAVID"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>25", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Peter, the reward of the elders who tend the flock of God is  </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an everlasting inheritance     </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">immorality </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the unfading crown of glory </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">prosperity</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 1 Peter 5:4, Peter states that when the Chief Shepherd appears, the elders who have tended the flock of God will receive the unfading crown of glory. This means that their reward is not a physical or material one, but a spiritual one that will never fade away.</div>", "topic": "CHRISTIANS AS JOINT HEIRS WITH CHRIST : THE BENEFITS OF BEING JOINT HEIRS WITH CHRIST"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>26", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Romans, Paul made it clear that believers were buried with christ so that when He is resurrected, they might  </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">rise again on the last day    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">walk in the newness of life </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be partakers of the gifts of God  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be completely renewed from their sin</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Romans 6:4, Paul explains that believers were buried with Christ through baptism into death in order that, just as Christ was raised from the dead through the glory of the Father, they too may live a new life. This means that believers are not just waiting for a future resurrection, but are called to live a new, transformed life right now.</div>", "topic": "NEW LIFE IN CHRIST : CONDITIONS AND BENEFITS OF NEW LIFE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>27", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Where is he who has been born King of the Jews..\"  <br/>  The statement above about Jesus' birth was made by </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Simeon    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Elizabeth, John's mother </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Anna  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the wise men</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement \"Where is he who has been born King of the Jews..\" was made by the wise men. This is recorded in the Bible in Matthew 2:2. The wise men were guided by a star to the place where Jesus was born and they asked this question to Herod the king.</div>", "topic": "THE BIRTH AND EARLY LIFE OF JESUS : THE BIRTH AND BOYHOOD OF JESUS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>28", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">On the occasion of Jesus' resurrection, the presence of the angel that rolled back the stone on His sepulchre caused     </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an earthquake     </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a windstorm  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a storm </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lightning</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">On the occasion of Jesus' resurrection, the presence of the angel that rolled back the stone on His sepulchre caused an earthquake. This is recorded in the Bible in Matthew 28:2. The earthquake occurred when the angel of the Lord descended from heaven, came and rolled back the stone and sat on it.</div>", "topic": "RESURRECTION, APPEARANCES AND ASCENSION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION AND APPEARANCE OF JESUS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>29", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The plant which the Lord appointed as shade over Jonah was to   </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">caution him    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">encourage him </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">educate him </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">chastise him</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Jonah, the plant which the Lord appointed as shade over Jonah was to educate him. God used the plant to teach Jonah about compassion. After Jonah was upset about the plant's death, God pointed out that Jonah cared about the plant, which came up in a night and perished in a night. And should not God care about the great city of Nineveh, which had more than a hundred and twenty thousand people who could not tell their right hand from their left, and also many animals?</div>", "topic": "GOD'S MESSAGE TO NINEVEH: JONAH AND HIS MESSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>30", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God forgave the Israelites and asked Jeremiah to proclaim His words toward the  </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">south    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">north </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">east </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">west</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Jeremiah, God forgave the Israelites and asked Jeremiah to proclaim His words toward the north. This is because the northern kingdom of Israel had been taken into captivity by the Assyrians. God was directing His message to them, promising that He would bring them back to their land.</div>", "topic": "CONCERN FOR JUDAH : RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF JUDAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>31", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Romans, for a believer to be justified by faith,the Law and the Prophets have to </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be in place </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be seperated </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">bear witness</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be united</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Romans 3:21, the Law and the Prophets bear witness to the righteousness of God through faith in Jesus Christ. This means that the Law and the Prophets testify or give evidence to the fact that believers are justified by faith.</div>", "topic": "JUSTIFICATION BY FAITH : MEANING AND BASIC CONDITIONS FOR JUSTIFICATION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>32", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Paul, one who speaks in tongues speaks to </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">angels    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">men</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">spirits</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 1 Corinthians 14:2, Paul states that anyone who speaks in a tongue does not speak to men but to God. This is because in a tongue, one speaks mysteries with the Spirit, which are understood by God.</div>", "topic": "SPIRITUAL GIFTS : THE DIFFERENT SPIRITUAL GIFTS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>33", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jehoshaphat did what was right in the sight of God but the people still sacrificed on the high places because he</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">did not take away the high places     </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">compromised later in life </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">did not destroy those who oppose him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">love the people and allow them to do their will</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jehoshaphat was a king who did what was right in the sight of God. However, the people still sacrificed on the high places because he did not take away the high places. High places were locations where ancient Israelites worshipped, and they were often associated with idolatrous practices. Jehoshaphat's failure to remove these places allowed the people to continue their sacrifices.</div>", "topic": "RELIGIOUS REFORMS IN JUDAH : CLEANSING OF THE TEMPLE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>34", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">What was the consequence of Gehazi's greed? </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Naaman's leprosy cleaved to him    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Elisha sent him on exile </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He was asked to cleanse the temple</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He became a slave to Naaman</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The consequence of Gehazi's greed was that Naaman's leprosy cleaved to him. Gehazi was the servant of Elisha, and he lied to Naaman to get gifts that Elisha had refused. When Elisha found out, he cursed Gehazi, saying that Naaman's leprosy would cling to Gehazi and his descendants forever.</div>", "topic": "GREED AND ITS EFFECTS : GEHAZI"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>35", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"I adjure you by the living God, tell us if you are the Christ, the son of God.\".  <br/>  Jesus was asked the question above during His trial before</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Pilate    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Herod </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the high priest</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the elders</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically in the book of Matthew 26:63, it was the high priest who asked Jesus if He was the Christ, the Son of God during His trial. Therefore, the correct answer is 'the high priest'.</div>", "topic": "THE TRIALS AND THE DEATH OF JESUS : THE TRIALS OF JESUS BEFORE THE HIGH PRIEST"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>36", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The two sons of Eli refused to listen to their father's instruction because </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they were ready to perish    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">it was the will of God  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they were following the instructions of the gods</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they were acting outside the will of God</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically in the book of 1 Samuel 2:12-25, Eli's sons, Hophni and Phinehas, were described as men who had no regard for the Lord or for the duties of the priests to the people. They were acting outside the will of God, which led to their downfall. Therefore, the correct answer is 'they were acting outside the will of God'.</div>", "topic": "PARENTAL RESPONSIBILITY : ELI AND SAMUEL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>37", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the second coming of the Lord according to Thessalonians, Jesus will descend from heaven with </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">trumpets    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">brimstone and fire </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a cry of command</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">angels</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to 1 Thessalonians 4:16, 'For the Lord himself will descend from heaven with a cry of command, with the voice of an archangel, and with the sound of the trumpet of God. And the dead in Christ will rise first.' Therefore, the correct answer is 'a cry of command'.</div>", "topic": "THE SECOND COMING OF CHRIST : THE SIGNS OF THE COMING OF CHRIST"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>38", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to James, he who doubts is like</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wind on the trees    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">flowers of the field  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">waves of the sea</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">dust in the desert</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to James 1:6, 'But let him ask in faith, with no doubting, for the one who doubts is like a wave of the sea that is driven and tossed by the wind.' Therefore, the correct answer is 'waves of the sea'.</div>", "topic": "DECISION-MAKING : RELIANCE ON A MEDIUM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>39", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"...I will blot out man whom I have created from the face of the ground. For I am sorry that I have made them. God made the statement above during Noah's time because</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the people refused to heed Noah's warning     </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the sons of God were not recognised by the people as His representatives </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the sons of God went into the daughters of men and they bore children</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the people refused to make atonement</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement was made by God during Noah's time because the sons of God went into the daughters of men and they bore children. This is a reference to Genesis 6:1-7, where it is stated that the sons of God saw that the daughters of men were attractive and they took as their wives any they chose. This led to a race of giants known as the Nephilim and it was one of the reasons God decided to destroy the earth with a flood.</div>", "topic": "THE COVENANT : THE FLOOD AND GOD'S COVENANT WITH NOAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>40", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Romans, every authority that exist is instituted by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">law    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">prophets </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">men</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Romans 13:1, every authority that exists is instituted by God. The verse states 'Let every person be subject to the governing authorities. For there is no authority except from God, and those that exist have been instituted by God.' This means that all authority comes from God and He is the one who establishes it.</div>", "topic": "CIVIC RESPONSIBILITY : THE NEED FOR OBEDIENCE TO AUTHORITY"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>41", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The LORD led the Israelites round by the way of the wilderness and not through that of the Philistines which was near because </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the Israelites preferred going through the wilderness   </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He didn't want them to encounter war and go back to Egypt </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He wanted the journey to be long</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He wanted to teach them patience and perseverance</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Exodus 13:17, it is stated that when Pharaoh let the people go, God did not lead them by way of the land of the Philistines, although that was near. For God said, 'Lest the people change their minds when they see war and return to Egypt.' Therefore, the reason was that God didn't want them to encounter war and go back to Egypt.</div>", "topic": "THE COVENANT : GOD'S COVENANT WITH ISRAEL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>42", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In His teaching on the parable of the sower, Jesus said that when anyone hears the word and does not understand it, it means that  </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he will fall away when tribulation and persecution arise    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the cares of this world and the delighting riches choked it up  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the evil one has come and snatched away what is sown in his heart</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">trials and temptations swept him off his feet  </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Matthew 13:19, Jesus explains the parable of the sower and says 'When anyone hears the word of the kingdom and does not understand it, the evil one comes and snatches away what has been sown in his heart.' Therefore, it means that the evil one has come and snatched away what is sown in his heart.</div>", "topic": "THE PARABLES : PARABLES OF THE KINGDOM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>43", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The remnant of the tribes that the children of Israel could not utterly destroy were made slaves by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Solomon    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Saul  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">David</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Rehoboam</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the Bible, specifically in the book of 1 Kings 9:20-21, it was Solomon who made the remnant of the tribes that the children of Israel could not utterly destroy into slaves. These people were the Amorites, the Hittites, the Perizzites, the Hivites, and the Jebusites, who were not of the children of Israel. They were made to pay tribute and were not exterminated by the Israelites as they were supposed to do according to God's command.</div>", "topic": "LEADERSHIP QUALITIES : SOLOMON"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>44", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the sermon of Jesus on the mount, the meek shall </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be satisfied    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">obtain mercy </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">inherit the earth</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">see God</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Sermon on the Mount, specifically in Matthew 5:5, Jesus said, 'Blessed are the meek, for they shall inherit the earth.' The meek, according to Jesus, are those who are humble and gentle, not proud and aggressive. The promise that they will 'inherit the earth' is an assurance of God's ultimate blessing and provision.</div>", "topic": "SERMON ON THE MOUNT : THE DEMANDS OF THE KINGDOM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>45", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Woe is me! For I am lost, for I am a man of unclean lips...\"  <br/>  What happened after Isaiah made the statement above?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The LORD put forth His hand and touched his mouth    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Seraphim touched his lips with a burning coal </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He was given a scroll to eat</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Seraphim lifted him on their wings</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Isaiah, after Isaiah made the statement \"Woe is me! For I am lost, for I am a man of unclean lips...\", a seraphim flew to him with a live coal in his hand, which he had taken with tongs from the altar. The seraphim touched Isaiah's mouth with it and said, \"Behold, this has touched your lips; your guilt is taken away, and your sin atoned for.\" (Isaiah 6:5-7). Therefore, the correct answer is that the Seraphim touched his lips with a burning coal.</div>", "topic": "HOLINESS AND DIVINE CALL : THE CALL OF ISAIAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>46", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Amos, God is described as one who builds His upper chambers in the heavens to depict His </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sovereignty    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wisdom </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">might</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">glory</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Amos, God is described as one who builds His upper chambers in the heavens. This is a depiction of His sovereignty. Sovereignty refers to supreme power or authority. In this context, it means that God has ultimate control over the heavens and the earth. Therefore, the correct answer is sovereignty.</div>", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD :GOD AS CREATOR AND CONTROLLER OF THE UNIVERSE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>47", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Set apart for me Barnabas and Saul for the work to which I have called them.\"  <br/>  According to the books of Acts, what work were the people mentioned above set apart for?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To take care of the Hellenist    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To heal the sick and raise the dead  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To receive new converts to the Church </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To preach the gospel to the Gentiles</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Acts, specifically Acts 13:2, Barnabas and Saul (who is also known as Paul) were set apart by the Holy Spirit for the specific work of preaching the gospel to the Gentiles. This was a significant event as it marked the beginning of Paul's missionary journeys, where he traveled extensively to spread the gospel to non-Jewish people (Gentiles).</div>", "topic": "MISSION TO THE GENTILES : THE COMMISSIONING AND MISSION OF PAUL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>48", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Paul in his letter to Philemon pleaded with him to accept Onesimus back as a </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">beloved son     </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">useful brethren </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">useful slave</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">beloved brother</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Philemon, Paul wrote a letter to Philemon, a fellow Christian, pleading with him to accept Onesimus back not as a slave, but as a 'useful brother' in Christ. Onesimus was a slave who had run away from Philemon, but during his time away, he had become a Christian under Paul's guidance. Paul's letter to Philemon is a plea for Christian brotherhood and forgiveness.</div>", "topic": "FORGIVENESS : PAUL’S TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>49", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Son of man, stand upon your feet, and I will speak with you.\"  <br/>  In the statement above, who was referred to as son of man?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Isaiah     </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ezekiel </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jeremiah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Amos</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'Son of Man' is used in the Bible to refer to various individuals, depending on the context. In the context of the given statement, it is referring to the prophet Ezekiel. This is evident in the book of Ezekiel, where God often addresses Ezekiel as 'Son of Man'.</div>", "topic": "HOLINESS AND DIVINE CALL : THE CALL OF EZEKIEL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2016>50", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Tell me whether you sold the land for so much.\"  <br/>  Peter's statement above to Sapphira was to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">test her sincerity    </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">make her guilty </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">make her repent</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ensure her salvation</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Acts, Peter asks Sapphira about the price of the land to test her sincerity. Sapphira and her husband Ananias had sold a piece of property and kept back part of the money for themselves, but claimed they had given all the money to the church. Peter's question was a test to see if Sapphira would tell the truth or continue the lie.</div>", "topic": "OPPOSITION TO THE GOSPEL MESSAGE : PERSECUTION OF PAUL"}];
